<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-425-442  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 425 442.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  July 6 1989 n1171 p11(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>The story so far .... (Department of Social Security automation)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Collins, Tony.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>History of automating the Department of Social Security (DSS)since 1964 is reviewed in light of DSS estimates that OperationalStrategy, the department's latest automation effort, willeventually cost 2 billion pounds sterling.andP;  Beginning in 1964computer centers were set up in four cities, but delays plaguedthe automation effort throughout the 1970s.andP;  A computer-aidedmechanization of local offices project (Camelot) was scrapped in1982 at a cost of at least 6 million pounds sterling and replacedwith Operational Strategy, which at that point was envisaged ascosting 700 million pounds sterling over 15 to 20 years whiledoing away with the need for 6,000 staffers.andP;  Cost estimates anddelays have escalated steadily since then, but the consultant onOperational Strategy says the problems are minor.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Great Britain. Department of Health and Social SecurityHistoryMismanagementIncreasing Costs.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Automating social security - the 25 years so far. (table)Operational Strategy: benefit-related projects under development.andO;(table)Projected costs to date of Operational Strategy. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>